'''Paul David Izzo''' ({{IPA|it|ˈittso|lang}}; born 6 January 1995) is an Australian professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Danish Superliga]] side [[Randers FC|Randers]] and the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia national team]].

Izzo graduated from [[Rostrevor College]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rostrevor.sa.edu.au/soccer-program.html | title=Soccer Program }}</ref> Izzo played youth football at the [[Australian Institute of Sport Football Program|Australian Institute of Sport]] before making his professional debut for [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]]. In 2015, he joined [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] before returning to Adelaide United in 2017.

==Club career==

===Adelaide United===
Izzo made his professional debut against the [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] away at [[Central Coast Stadium|Bluetongue Stadium]] on 1 December 2012, replacing [[Eugene Galeković]], who was unavailable as a result of international duties. His first home game appearance for Adelaide United was against [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] on 7 December 2012, in a 4-2 win.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/adelaideunited/players/Paul-Izzo/4924 | title = Paul Izzo | publisher = footballaustralia.com.au | access-date = 18 July 2012 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120930081543/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/adelaideunited/players/Paul-Izzo/4924 | archive-date = 30 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe229939/paul-izzo/ | title = Paul Izzo | publisher = worldfootball.net | access-date = 18 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/aleague/matchcentre/lineup/Adelaide-United-FC-v-Melbourne-Victory-FC-Hyundai-A-League/2659 | title = Adelaide United FC vs Melbourne Victory FC: Team lineup | publisher = footballaustralia.com.au | access-date = 16 December 2012 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029204551/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/aleague/matchcentre/lineup/Adelaide-United-FC-v-Melbourne-Victory-FC-Hyundai-A-League/2659 | archive-date = 29 October 2013 }}</ref>

===Central Coast Mariners===
Izzo was released by Adelaide United on 8 July 2015, and subsequently signed with the Mariners for two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ccmariners.com.au/article/news-izzo-inks-with-mariners/vp1hv3g3tsax17dacggwr8luu|publisher=[[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]]|title=Izzo inks with Mariners|date=8 July 2015|access-date=8 July 2015|archive-date=2 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902013820/http://www.ccmariners.com.au/article/news-izzo-inks-with-mariners/vp1hv3g3tsax17dacggwr8luu|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Return to Adelaide United===
In April 2017, Izzo returned to his hometown club, Adelaide United, on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://outside90.com/i-always-wanted-to-come-back-adelaide-united-confirm-paul-izzo-signing-207/|title="I always wanted to come back" – Adelaide United confirm Paul Izzo signing|author=Fruci, Joel|date=19 April 2017|access-date=19 April 2017|publisher=Outside90.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419194604/http://outside90.com/i-always-wanted-to-come-back-adelaide-united-confirm-paul-izzo-signing-207/|archive-date=19 April 2017}}</ref>

===Xanthi===
In October 2020, Izzo was transferred to Greek club [[Xanthi F.C.|Xanthi]] for an undisclosed fee, following a few Australian players and coach [[Tony Popovic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ftbl.com.au/news/instrumental-adelaide-a-league-star-joins-greek-club-554201|title='Instrumental' Adelaide A-League star joins Greek club|first=Lucas|last=Radbourne|newspaper=FTBL|date=1 October 2020}}</ref>

=== Melbourne Victory ===
On 8 July 2022, Izzo returned to Australia, joining [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] as a free agent, and signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |last=apavlidis |date=2022-07-08 |title=Melbourne Victory signs Paul Izzo |url=https://melbournevictory.com.au/news/melbourne-victory-signs-paul-izzo |access-date=2023-12-11 |website=Melbourne Victory}}</ref> In the [[2023–24 A-League Men|2023–24 A-League Men play-offs]] against cross-town rivals [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]], Izzo made nine saves, including one on a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], in regular time, before saving three penalties and scoring one himself in the penalty shootout, thus helping Victory reach the semi-finals.

=== Randers ===
On 9 July 2024, Izzo joined [[Danish Superliga]] club [[Randers FC|Randers]] for an undisclosed fee,<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 July 2024 |title=Paul Izzo departs Melbourne Victory for European opportunity |url=https://melbournevictory.com.au/news/paul-izzo-departs-melbourne-victory-for-european-opportunity/ |access-date=9 July 2024 |website=Melbourne Victory}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=9 July 2024 |title=Randers FC henter Paul Izzo |url=https://randersfc.dk/nyheder-superliga/2024/juli/randers-fc-henter-paul-izzo |access-date=9 July 2024 |website=Randers FC |language=da}}</ref> signing a three-year contract.<ref name=":0" />

== International career ==
[[File:Paul Izzo 2013.jpg|thumb|Izzo with the [[Australia national under-20 association football team|Young Socceroos]] in 2013]]
Izzo represented Australia at [[Australia national under-20 association football team|U20]] level at the [[2012 AFC U-19 Championship]] in [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=NSW |first=Football |date=2012-10-23 |title=Paul Okon names Qantas Young Socceroos squad for AFC U-19 Championship |url=https://footballnsw.com.au/2012/10/23/paul-okon-names-qantas-young-socceroos-squad-for-afc-u-19-championship/ |access-date=2023-12-11 |website=Football NSW |language=en-US}}</ref> and at the [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in [[Turkey]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=FIFA U-20 World Cup Turkey 2013™: Australia |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/u20/turkey2013/teams/1888243 |access-date=2023-12-12 |website=www.fifa.com |language=en}}</ref>

He was first called up for the senior Socceroos squad on 28 August 2021, for [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against [[China national football team|China]] and [[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-08-28 |title=27 players destined for Doha as Socceroos get set for final phase of AFC Asian Qualifying |url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/september-squad-announcement |access-date=2023-12-11 |website=www.socceroos.com.au |language=en}}</ref>

On 5 September 2025, Izzo made his debut for the Australian senior team, starting against [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] in the first of the 2025 [[Soccer Ashes]] games and keeping a clean sheet in a 1–0 win.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2025-09-05 |title=Live: Red-hot Irankunda starts on the bench as Socceroos take on New Zealand |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-09-05/socceroos-new-zealand-live-blog/105736610 |access-date=2025-09-05 |work=ABC News |language=en-AU}}</ref>

